This is a popular place, but we knew that going in. We showed up around 9 AM for brunch on a Saturday & there were about 20 people ahead of us. You just put your name on a chalkboard inside & that's the wait list. Definitely get there early though - by the time we left, there were at least 2x as many people waiting outside. Would also recommend taking an Uber, not walking - even in the daylight, it's not a great area. We got the chocolate beignets to start - they're HUGE and could be all you need to order. SO good though. For drinks, my boyfriend got a bloody & I got a mimosa; we were both meh on the drinks. The small mimosa was definitely not the price. I ordered the Andouille Sausage & Cheddar Cheese Omelette, which came with home style potatoes & a biscuit. It was pretty good - I wanted a scramble, so basically just mashed up the eggs & it worked! My boyfriend got the French Toast and wasn't all that impressed. Pretty plain & he didn't think it was worth the wait for a table. Overall, decent place if you can go early enough to get a table without a long wait!

The pork belly grits was the other dish that stood out. The grits were absolutely delicious and cheesy. The pork belly wasn't as crispy as I hoped and it was small. Even with that small bite it was delicious and went well with the grits. Even though they looked good from pictures, the fried chicken Benedict and gumbo were nothing special. I would come here again for their beignet and grits, but on a weekday where you don't have to wait almost two hours.

    1 check-in

    Brenda's is a half step above a hole in the wall. It's surrounded by homeless people and urine soaked sidewalks, but the food is pretty damn good. I'm not sure we got the typical 'BSF' experience based on reading all the other reviews, but it was still a great meal.

    We came in the late afternoon and got seated immediately thank God. Our server, and the other servers based on my observations, weren't the friendliest people in the world. But the got the job done.

    The coffee (Community Coffee) is probably my favorite brand. Smooth, silky, and light. I ordered the french toast against my servers advice and I'm glad I did. Very sweet but with a good depth of flavor. The pecan spread it came with was money.

    Obviously the beignets are bomb. We didn't like the crawfish one, super fishy, but the rest were really good. The chocolate in the chocolate beignet was delicious. Rich and creamy.

    Also ordered two drumsticks on the side. They were really freakin good. I love the breading they use. It's got a very slight hint of spice that I've never had before. Highly recommend the fried chicken.

    Pumpkin pancake that was on special sucked. Like literally not good at all. It tasted like semi sweet Play Doh and had the same consistency. I had like two bites of it. Thumbs down

    Atmosphere was cool. Food was good. Service was eh.

    Here's my overall ratings:
    Atmosphere- 4/5
    Service- 2.5/5
    Quality/value- 3.5/5
    Food- 4/5
    Coffee- 4.5/5

    FOOD:
    (1) BFC, $12.75 - two pieces of fried chicken served with french fries, biscuits, and cole saw! 3.5 stars - I was kinda expecting a little bit more... cause people been raving about it!
    (2) Shrimp and Grits, $13.75 - I think this is one of my favorite!!! 5 stars to shrimp and grits. The grits was like mixed in with cheese or something - very flavorful and shrimp cooked perfectly! It was worth it's price!  
    (3) Flight Bignets, $11.50 - came with 4 different bignets! Nutella, apples, plain, and crab roll like! Came out kinda cold... but it was too much food for us... so I took it home and warmed it up and it was delish! Nutella was good with wine! YUMS!
